Crossposted-To: comp.os.linux
From: linux@fylz.com (Linux Journal)
Subject: Re: SunWorld on Linux
Date: Thu, 25 Nov 1993 04:37:44 GMT

Bill Heiser (bill@bhhome.ci.net) wrote:
: linux@fylz.com (Linux Journal) writes:

: >My biggest objection to the sidebar on Linux is that it implied that
: >SLS was Linux and Yggdrasil was Linux on CD-ROM.  It gave no feeling
: >for the spirit (for lack of a better word) of Linux nor did it explain
: >how SLS and Yggdrasil fit into the whole Linux picture.
: > -- Phil Hughes


: I think there are at least some of us who RUN LINUX who *still* don't
: really know what you described above.  In my case, I know there are
: different flavors, and each comes with a different set of utilities,
: but I don't know much about what differentiates them.

: In which FAQ would I find this info?  (or are you writing one now? :-)

Ok, let me translate.  (Gee, here I am editor of Linux Journal and I don't
make sense? :-) )

By the "spirit of Linux" I am talking about the amazing cooperative effort
that is going on to make Linux a reality.  The sidebar in the article was
titled someting like _SLS Linux System_ and went on to describe an
opeerating system that sounded like a product of Soft Landing Software
with no pointers to the fact that Linux was this effort of many and that
SLS was one of the "packages".  It went on to say that SLS was available
on floppy disks.  Then it said that it (where "it" doesn't indicate
there was anything different -- just the same old Linux) was also available
on CD-ROM from Yggdrasil.

In other words, the sidebar was true -- you can get "a" Linux on floppies
from SLS and "a" Linux on CD-ROM from Yggdrasil.  But it sure didn't do
any work toward painting the real Linux picture.  This is why I offered
to write an article on Linux for Sun World.

There really isn't any FAQ that does justice to the choice of Linux
packages that are available.  I have written a short story about what
is the right answer for your situation and sent it to many people.  I
will probably write an expanded version as an article for Linux Journal.
Once it is done I have no objection with making it available to the
net as well.

   -- Phil Hughes

