From: mark@datasoft.com (Mark Buckaway)
Subject: 4 COM ports that share IRQ3,4
Date: Fri, 26 Nov 1993 03:20:48 GMT

I posted a message suggesting this is possible. Running 4 serial ports
where only IRQ3 and IRQ4 are used (i.e. shared). I got numerous responses
asking for the information. I have posted it below.

DISCLAIMER: I did not write the following. I can testify that it does work
if and only if germanium diodes and 470 ohm resistors are used. DO NOT
ATTEMPT THIS ON YOUR SERIAL CARD UNLESS YOU KNOW WHAT A DIODE AND RESISTOR
ARE AND HOW TO SOLDER PROPERLY. You can easily destroy two good serial
cards if you don't know what you are doing. Use a grounded soldering iron.

Someone might want to add this to the serial FAQ.

==================================


  If you're the hardware hacking type, the following is a message I sent a
friend about this.  Works great, without too much effort.

---
  I'm not sure if I ever told you of my final solution to the problem.  It's
sleazy, but it works fine.  I did a diode ORing of the interrupt lines.
I've run two ports simultaneously without any problems.  One thing I
noticed while doing testing is that there is a huge difference in
processing overhead between 16550 UARTs and 8250 UARTs.  At 38400 baud,
the 8250 was really dragging the system down.  At 38400, the 16550s were
hardly noticable.  Nasty ASCII drawing to follow:

                  
                     IRQ Jumper Berg
                        Pins
                     |        |   
                     |        |
                     V        V
                        |\ |
 IRQ from COM1 UART  0--| >|--0--+----------------> Backplane IRQ4 of card 1
                        |/ |     |
                                 \
                                 /  470 ohm resistor
                                 \
                                 |
                               Ground
   

                        |\ |
 IRQ from COM2 UART  0--| >|--0--+----------------> Backplane IRQ3 of card 1
                        |/ |     |
                                 \
                                 /  470 ohm resistor
                                 \
                                 |
                               Ground

                        |\ |
 IRQ from COM3 UART  0--| >|--0-------------------> Backplane IRQ4 of card 2
                        |/ |  


                        |\ |
 IRQ from COM4 UART  0--| >|--0-------------------> Backplane IRQ3 of card 2
                        |/ |


  This has some advantages (and some disadvantages).

  The advantages:

  It works.

  It's backwards compatible.

  The only real modification you have to make to the card is the
addition of the resistors to the first one.  I put the diodes in place
of the IRQ jumper selection on the serial cards (takes some careful soldering).

  By just replacing the IRQ jumpers with diodes, you can string as many serial
ports on an IRQ as your software and number of card slots will support
(they all have to be uniquely addressed).

  Linux works perfectly with this setup out of the box (earlier bugs
have been fixed).

  The disadvantages:

  Electrically a bit hokey.  The 470 ohm resistor is on the small side,
[added note: my friend used 1K resistors with no problems]
but the drivers that are used for the interrupts are tanks and should be
able to provide sufficient source current.  You should use a germanium
diode for a low voltage drop.  I measured the drop of a bunch of small
signal diodes (silicon) out of my junk box and used the ones with the
smallest drop.

  DOS still won't work for two ports simultaneously (if you care :)
because the software drivers won't handle two-interrupts-at-once cases
right.

Cliff
-- 
